text: The image displays architectural drawings for a school, featuring a detailed floor plan at the top with labeled rooms including classrooms, a gym, cafeteria, library, art room, and support spaces like bathrooms and small teaching areas. Two elevation views below show the building’s exterior, characterized by a geometric, fragmented design on the left and more structured sections on the right, with sections labeled AA and BB. The layout combines functional educational spaces with an expressive architectural style, using black-and-white line work typical of technical blueprints. Key elements include the strategic arrangement of classrooms around central communal areas and the integration of outdoor or semi-outdoor spaces suggested by the fragmented geometric patterns on the elevations. The drawings collectively illustrate the building’s spatial organization and aesthetic approach.

pg. 1
A Design Case Study in the Effectiveness of Generative Models
R. Spencer Steenblik RA, Omar Dib PhD, Jonathan Hill
Indiana University Bloomington, Wenzhou-Kean University, Indiana University
Abstract
Similar to the slow food movement, there may be a need to take in, and be more aware of every step throughout the
design process. "Slow Design can indeed have a positive impact on wellbeing." In another context, Minsky discusses
training an AI model and states "slow learning.. smoothes away uncertainties due to noise". Today with generative
AI tools able to ideate and visualize incesently toward an accelerated design process, we run the risk of getting caught
in a place where design happens in front of the designer more than through the designer. Minksky elaborates " it will

at last become economical to match human beings in real time with really large machines. This means that we can
work toward programming what will be, in effect, "thinking aids." In the years to come, we expect that these man-
machine systems will share, and perhaps for a time be dominant, in our advance toward the development of "artificial
intelligence."
This article considers workflows for several AI models in collaboration with designers to tackle a real world design
problem. We will spend time comparing and contrasting how these models impact design workflows, making
observations along the way about enhancing features and again where fidelity is lost. We will include Neural Style

Transfer(NST) (an older generative AI model) which isn't as streamlined nor high fidelity. We will briefly discuss
some relevent technicalities of this older model in order to illucidate opportunities of an older model with lower
fidelity than the current state of the art. The lower quality, sketchy output creates ambiguity for the designer to
interpret. Potentially allowing the imagination and the designers intuition to play a larger role than with some of the
newer models. Working with machine learning neural style transfer (NST) can allow the designers to consider
possibilities humanity may not otherwise allow ourselves to imagine. This project tests this hypothisis. Perhaps we
should linger in the "man-machine system" paradigm a little longer even if we are able to go further?
Keywords

The image depicts a surreal, intricate mechanical landscape dominated by large circular structures resembling domes or gears, interconnected by complex wiring and industrial frameworks. A central tower with ornate, layered patterns rises above a chaotic arrangement of metallic components, while tiny human figures near the bottom provide scale against the massive machinery. The scene blends organic and industrial elements in a muted, aged palette of browns and yellows, evoking a dreamlike, futuristic ruin or a hyper-detailed steampunk workshop. Layered textures and overlapping mechanical parts create a sense of depth and overwhelming complexity, with a bright light source illuminating the central area. The overall composition feels both alien and familiar, merging architectural grandeur with intricate, almost biological machinery.

pg. 2
This work outlines an approach to using neural style transfer (NST) in a novel way as a part of the early architectural
design process. We seek to use the tool in a way unintended by its creators, for results different from many examples
or use cases. (Liu et al 2021) (Liu 2021)(Wang 2021)
The work presented herein attempts to blur the lines between architectural design, story telling, digital media,
computer science and other disciplines. The objective of the effort is to inspire humanity toward a brighter future
through imagining and instantiating possible futures. Divergent from many other documented use cases within the
design process, this use case of NST focuses on a more intuitive, iterative, feedback loop between designer and the

computational process. (Fig 3) We attempt to achieve a guided vision, possibly beyond the potential conceptions of
the designer in unaided circumstances to conceive of the outcomes, or potential design schemes. Built on several
speculative architectural workshops, art exhibitions, and design studios at Tongji DigitalFUTURES, FutureLab
Shanghai, Longxi Art Museum, and Wenzhou-Kean University, respectively, this paper seeks ontological uncertainty
between the artist and a cognitive prosthetic using the machine learning technologies of a convolutional neural
network (CNN), and more specifically NST in the early design phase for novel design solutions.
The collection of NST compositions represented in this article are primarily possible futures. One might ask about

the merit of compositions that do not seem to be feasible or viable as constructed architecture. Yet these blue sky
explorations can exist only digitally, or possibly become a part of humanity's built reality at some point in the future.
Regardless of their final instantiation, by very conception, these possibilities become exactly that, a possibility,
otherwise impossible.  This paper will first outline our process. Afterward consider some of the lineage from which
this work springs and the potential power of the speculative world building process. (Young 2020) Next we will
consider the low hanging fruit of instantiating these places at least virtually in the metaverse and/or through VR,
animation as a way to solidify their somewhat timid present reality.
2. Background

Recent advances in Artificial Intelligence have demonstrated the ability of Deep Learning models such as
Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) to generate artistic imageries by extracting and recombining the content of
an image and a style. This process of applying different styles to an image content via a CNN architecture is usually
referred to as Neural Style Transfer (NST) (Gatys et al., 2016).
Due to its visually plausible results, the research in NST has amassed a significant amount of attention and effort from
academic and industry practitioners. Various novel approaches have been proposed to improve the original NST
architecture or extend it to cope with new application settings. In addition, many successful industrial applications

have been developed and begun to deliver commercial benefits. For example, in social communication, NST
applications have aided people in creating artworks and sharing their art paintings on social media platforms, which
can be regarded as a new form of social communication. In that regard, Prisma1 and deeparteffects2 have been among
the digital applications that have successfully provided NST as a service for many users. Similarly, in the contribution
of (Reimann et al., 2018), authors introduced “MaeSTrO,” a novel mobile application that facilitates a creative and
localized style transfer editing process. Beyond social communication, NST has been a precious assisted tool for
painters and designers. Nowadays, NST can make it more convenient for a painter to create a digital artwork of a

particular style. Moreover, NST algorithms have produced a large panel of ready-to-use fashion components in
various styles. This has immensely improved the efficiency of fashion designers and stylized CAD drawings and
significantly reduced manufacturing costs (Dubey et al., 2020).
NST has also been applied in the digital entertainment sector, such as in video games, via automatically stylizing a
video scene into a particular artistic style in real-time. In this convention, (Chen et al.,2018) proposed CartoonGAN,
a Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) based framework, to transform photos of real-world scenes into cartoon-
style images with unpaired and cartoon images for training. Another work by (Cao et al., 2018) proposed CariGANs,

an unpaired GAN architecture for face to caricatures translation; the model explicitly represents the geometric
exaggeration and appearance stylization.
1 https://prisma-ai.com/
2 https://www.deeparteffects.com/

pg. 3
Technically speaking, generating images in NST methods is not unique. It rather depends on the usage of the
optimization process and its workflow within the NST architecture. With that, image generation in NST can be
classified into 1) optimization-based methods (Li, C. et al., 2016), where the synthesized output is directly generated
by optimizing the content and style loss functions within the feature space of the CNN model. This method is
relatively slow but usually leads to a higher synthesized quality, 2) feed-forward methods (Chen et al., 2017) that
allow the stylized output images to be generated by a single iteration, however, the output is restrained by those pre-

trained style images, and 3) arbitrary methods (Huang et al., 2017) that generate stylized outputs within a single
iteration given arbitrary style images. Despite improving computation efficiency, Feed-forward and arbitrary methods
often sacrifice the synthesized quality.
Based on their style modeling, NST techniques can be classified into 1) statistics-based and patch-based
methods (Sheng et al., 2018). The former aims to represent the image style via some statistics. In this convention, the
Gram matrix is one of the first introduced and commonly used statistical metrics for NST; it computes the correlation
between the various feature maps extracted at each layer of CNN.  The Gram matrix has been notably improved and

extended by recent NST methods.  For example, (Risser et al., 2017) found that the large difference in the means and
variances of feature maps is not fully reflected in the Gram matrix; to handle this imbalance, the authors integrated
the histogram and TV losses within the Gram matrix. Likewise, (Li, S. et al., 2017) integrated a Laplacian loss to
preserve the detailed structures of the content image and eliminate the artifacts. Other popular statistics in NST use
the mean and variance for style quantification. For instance, (Li, Y. et al., 2017) presented a feed forward NST via a
direct matching of feature covariance of the extracted feature activations to a given style image. Similarly, (Huang et

al., 2017) introduced a novel NST method that enables arbitrary style transfer in real-time via an adaptive instance
normalization layer that aligns the mean and variance of the content features with those of the style features.
Based on Markov Random Field (MRF) and CNNs, patch-based NST methods directly extract and match the local
neural patches of the content and style images (Li, C. et al., 2016). In this concept, for each patch in the synthesized
feature activation, a similar patch in the style activation is matched, and the style loss is calculated as the cumulative
distances between those patches. Interestingly, patch and statistics-based NST methods have been combined as in the

work of (Sheng et al., 2018) by firstly applying a whitening and coloring transformation to obtain aligned feature
activations, on which a patch swapping transformation is then performed. Attentional-based NST has recently been
proposed, which can also be regarded as patch-based style transfer. In this regard, (Park et al., 2019) and (Deng et al.,
2020) introduced a style-attentional network to match the style features into the content features and a self-attention
mechanism for multi-stroke style transfer respectively.
As far as the evaluation of NST algorithms is considered, the process is not entirely straightforward and remains an
open and crucial challenge. Essentially, two major evaluation methodologies can be employed in the field of NST:

qualitative and quantitative (Wang Z. et al., 2021). The former relies on the aesthetic judgments of observers, and its
results are related to many factors (e.g., profiles of participants). In contrast, the quantitative evaluation focuses on
specific metrics, which include time complexity, loss variation, etc.
3. Neural Style Transfer (NST)
In this section, we detail a Neural Style Transfer (NST) model that is used explicitly for an artistic style. In this
architecture, a pretrained VGG-16 model on the ImageNet dataset is employed for the extraction of features
representing the semantics of an image's content and its underlying style.
1) Image Content:

with the set of existing filters in each of the CNN’s layers. A layer 𝑙 often includes 𝑁𝑙 ∈ℤ+ distinct filters to extract
the various semantics of the image's content, and 𝑁𝑙 feature maps each of size 𝑀𝑙 ∈ℤ+ to encode the pixel values.
Hence, the output of each layer 𝑙 can be represented in the form of a matrix 𝐹𝑙∈ℝ𝑁𝑙∗𝑀𝑙, with 𝐹𝑖𝑗

3) Style Transfer Algorithm
In machine learning or deep learning architectures, the model parameters are optimized beforehand using an
optimization technique such as Gradient Descent. As a result, a model with its optimized parameters is obtained
whereby a new input can be processed. Oppositely, transferring the style of an image 𝑎̂ onto another image 𝑏̂ is
accomplished in our architecture by repeatedly optimizing the pixel values of a newly constructed image,  𝑐̂, so that
the style of 𝑐̂ matches the style of 𝑎̂ and its content duplicates the content of 𝑏̂. Therefore, the concept of a "model"
optimized a priori is absent in our usage of NST. Instead, a separate optimization process occurs every time a new

input takes place in the network.
More specifically, at the first stage of the process, a new image 𝑐̂ is initialized to some random noise. Afterwards, a
joined loss function comprising the style loss 𝐿𝑠𝑡𝑦𝑙𝑒(𝑐̂, 𝑎̂) and content loss 𝐿𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑛𝑡(𝑐̂,𝑏̂) is optimized. The total loss
function is defined as follows:
𝐿𝑡𝑜𝑡𝑎𝑙(𝑎̂, 𝑏̂,𝑐̂) =  𝛼𝐿𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑛𝑡(𝑐̂, 𝑏̂) +  𝛽𝐿𝑠𝑡𝑦𝑙𝑒(𝑐̂, 𝑎̂)
Where 𝛼 and 𝛽 ∈ℤ+ are hyperparameters specifying the contribution weights of the content and style toward the
total loss. A large 𝛼𝛽
⁄  ratio indicates the content of the image  𝑏̂ is emphasized more in the constructed image 𝑐̂,
while a small 𝛼𝛽
⁄  value allocates more effort to the style of  𝑐̂.
The first step in the algorithm is to extract the content and style feature maps. To do so, the style image 𝑎̂ is passed

through the network, and its style representation 𝐴𝑙 is computed across all layers using the Gram Matrix.
Subsequently, the content image 𝑏̂ is passed through the network, and its content representation 𝐵𝑙 at each layer is
stored.  Next, the constructed image 𝑐̂, whose pixel values are randomly initialized, is passed through the network,
and its style matrix 𝐺𝑙 and content activations 𝐹𝑙 are computed.  At each layer involved in the style representation,
the mean square errors between the two Gram Matrices 𝐺𝑙 and 𝐴𝑙 is computed for the sake of 𝐿𝑠𝑡𝑦𝑙𝑒(𝑐̂, 𝑎̂) loss
function. Additionally, the mean squared difference between 𝐹𝑙 and 𝐵𝑙 activations is computed for the sake of

computing the loss 𝐿𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑛𝑡(𝑐̂, 𝑏̂). The total loss 𝐿𝑡𝑜𝑡𝑎𝑙(𝑎̂, 𝑏̂,𝑐̂) is then computed as a linear combination between the
content 𝐿𝑐𝑜𝑛𝑡𝑒𝑛𝑡(𝑐̂, 𝑏̂), and the 𝐿𝑠𝑡𝑦𝑙𝑒(𝑐̂,𝑎̂) loss. Moreover, as in a Gradient Descent optimizer, the derivative of the
total loss is computed with respect to the pixel values of 𝑐̂ and dynamically adjusted via back-propagation.  The
process is repeated until 𝑐̂ matches the style features of 𝑎̂ and its content features match 𝑏̂.

4. Novel Methods Toward Future Possibilities
Figure 2 This diagram outlines the artistic process, of “Plant First City” by Shannon Xiaotong Shi 施晓彤. A straightforward subversion
of the NST tool by combining two “non-style” images to conceive of and create a novel urban environment.
This paper reflects on a collection of works by the author and collaborators that seek to subvert the intended use case
of NST. Our process utilized NST built on VGG16 and subsequently VGG19 conceived by Oxford's Visual Geometry
Group (VGG, 19 denoting the number of layers in the network).(Gatys et al 2016)(Hassan 2021) The technology is
designed to apply the style from, for example, a famous painting such as "Starry Night" by Van Gough, and apply it
to a base image such as a photo taken with your phone.

Our unconventional approach to the process involves the intuition of the designer as a part of the style transfer and
compositing process. We outline a use case for NST in the early design phase of an architectural project where the
designer goes back and forth between the NST process and other inputs toward an optimized result which meets the
subjective, intuitive exploratory criteria of the designer. Our process encourages the mis-use of the NST process
through subverting the labeling mechanisms inherent to the NST process; encouraging a style image to be used as a
base image and what may be considered a base image as a style, or in other cases we forgo the style all together and

instead opt to only feed the system base images; starving the system for a style. We also encourage the compositing
of multiple more traditional NST images into a single composition. After several NST exercises the design can then
respond to the collected results in a collaging exercise to create outcomes that otherwise would have been impractical.
(Fig. 2)

The image displays a creative process collage with multiple panels illustrating a digital art and architecture workflow. It features vibrant, pastel-colored abstract cityscapes on the left and right, alongside software screenshots of Blender (showing 3D modeling) and Grasshopper (visual programming for city structures). Text in both English and Chinese explains steps like generating organic art via DeepArt, refining models with architectural elements, and rendering final scenes. The sequence shows a progression from initial concept sketches to a detailed, whimsical futuristic cityscape with geometric buildings and colorful textures. The layout uses arrows to guide the viewer through the iterative design process, highlighting tools like Blender and Grasshopper for creating stylized urban environments.

pg. 7
Figure 3 Comparing the process of a typical NST to the hybrid approach outlined in this paper.
The aesthetic of an NST often approaches something akin to computational impressionism.(Lee 2019) This style
inherently lends itself to the potential for an emotional response from a viewer. Paired with unexpected, uncanny, or
emotionally vivid elements the compositions often approach the sublime.(Kant 1914) These results can then be taken
by the designer as a prompt, for further speculation and development based on a set of constraints. Our process
maintains that NST output commonly provides a small peek into a potential world. It is up to the designer to take the
prompt further and develop what they see in the image. After the designers develop their interpretations and

speculations as a more flushed out image; often literally expanding the frame and providing elements of scale and
context, a more traditional modeling process can follow, with the outcomes moving from not possible to conceived
and on to a navigable experience, and possibly built. Although, there are several developing technologies with
increasing capabilities able to translate single images into 3D digital models. Exploring these tools will be at the heart
of future work in this research.
Several of the use cases of NST within this framework have resulted in the output weighing significantly on the final
outcomes of the architectural design project. Three of the architectural design studios that have used this process have

ended with results which have been directly inspired by the early visioning produced with the designer and the NST
process. In the spring of 2022 the author ran an architectural design studio with co-instructor David Vardy, where
NST was a core aspect to the early design phase. Later in the semester the results were curated in the “Computational
Impressionism 无极之地” exhibition at the Longxi Art Museum in Zeya, Zhejiang Province.(see Fig. 5)

The students began by doing site research. collecting material samples, natural artifacts, photographs, etc. They also
began processing the programmatic requirements, and in turn begin thinking about precedent projects. All of these
inputs inform the subject matter input into the NST process. Yet with the distinct interest in subverting the style
transfer in favor of a mixing of ideas, the outcomes demand new subjective interpretations of the original object, not
allowing the observer (including the designer) to be passive about their experience viewing the outcome from the

exercise. The outcomes of this superficial process generally lack scale and context. The designer is called to engage
with the art. The original subject is often no longer readily recognizable. Instead, the designer must layer their own
psychological imprint on the piece to interpret it. It is the opportunity of the designer to define both. As mentioned
earlier this happens through an expanding of the frame to define elements such as horizon, orientation, scale, and
provide some reference indicators. The results of all of these efforts are both inspiring and important in the
development of hybrid intelligence within creative disciplines.

5. Imagination: a Pioneering Effort for Humanity
Much of what drives design are performative aspects of the outcomes, yet if we are only driven by the utilitarian
requirements, we will never allow ourselves the opportunity to imagine alternatives. By pushing beyond what is
conceivable we enable new possibilities for the future.(Rhees 2009) This can be referred to as the development of
possible futures. It is a significant part of guiding the future. Hybrid intelligent processes such as style transfer can

play a key role in this and other problems humanity faces.
This research project builds on the heritage of the digital studios pioneered by Bernard Tschumi, and before him the
work of Syd Mead (1933-2019), Lebbeus Woods (1940-2012), Roger Dean (1944), and others. We see the legacy of
the Columbia University digital studio effort going on to create such projects as the digital Guggenheim, New City,
and has even influenced Hollywood world building see examples from Alex McDowell and the World Building
Media Lab at the University of Southern California. Yet this is not the only lineage of computation influencing the
future of urban conceptions. We have seen, particularly in the last ten years, the influence of computational methods

such as parametric, procedural, and machine learning rework the possibilities of creativity to incorporate computation
as a collaborator.
Beyond those technical aspects driving creativity and innovation, there are other stirrings including more cultural
ones such as the post-digital movement which has worked to flatten and colorize predominant conceptions of our
future. One could argue that the digital screen is the ultimate flattening, and yet the digital screen offers so much in
terms of dimensionality. The imagery produced together with the artist and the computer using NST arguably creates
a new aesthetic, a new style entirely, obviously grounded in a strong foundation briefly explored above. Yet this

aesthetic quite possibly may have been previously out of reach without computational collaboration.
The work that this group has undertaken is inherently optimistic and is rooted in questions such as: What kind of a
world would you like to exist in if some limitation was removed? What possible futures could embody more
sustainable circumstances for humanity? What is the ideal community for an individual? For industry? For
community? What elements are needed in order to cultivate the most conducive environments? What methods of
digital representation are optimal for expressing these ideas? How can one question traditional typologies and
outdated organizational systems for the benefit of humanity? How do diverse family structures, demographics, and
living/working styles affect the city?

this work she considers the absurd possibility of a city where plants receive the primary and first consideration. What

6. Virtual Habitation
Figure 7 This is a frame taken from “Parkour in Mars City”, an Unreal Engine simulation by Alex Guo Yupeng 郭玉鹏 and Ted Kaiyuan
Feng 冯开元, based upon a series of NST compositions. (Yupeng Et al 2021)
The technologies necessary to create complex digital worlds using automated computational methods seems to still
be an illusive matter. NST and related technologies by themselves fall short of being a creative force in 3D world
building alone.(Zhang Et al 2020) Yet NST can be a part of a collaborative process with designers in order to directly
inform and participate in “world building”(Young 2020)  minimally for virtual spaces. As virtual spaces are not

limited by the constraints outside of computational environments, the NST results can then be taken by the designer
as a prompt, for further speculation and development based on a set of constraints.
NST seems to allow designers/architects to envision realities outside of the constraints of currently understood
physics. This allows those who experience the place to engage in potentially impossible phenomena under any other
circumstances. For example the work highlighted in Fig. 7 again deals with an extra-planetary parkour experience
designed around the divergence in gravitational properties between our own earth and what might be; elsewhere. How
does our design of space change based on this parameter? This example lets you virtually realize those differences.

These landscapes become a “digital shadow” of a physical landscape that has not yet been realized. These shadows
have a life of their own outside of any physical reality. The ambition is that through these virtual prototypes we can
iterate faster through possibilities toward a better future.
7. Conclusion
We have explored some pedagogical case studies, strengthening the argument that this process can yield compelling
results that inspire and demand questioning, and quite possibly yield unconventional approaches to real world
problems. NST has many use cases, but the most interesting may be the misuse of the tool by not simply taking the
transfer at face value, but by subverting the labeling methods employed in the training set of the model to create

unexpected results that take NST beyond just transferring a style toward honest unique creation. With this use case it
is not difficult for the imagery to help in the process of speculating about future possibilities. Synthetic intelligence
allow us to move past human conceptions considering realities we may not deem feasible. Human imagination is
always a precursor to what becomes reality. Thinking beyond our current conceptions of reality is essential to move
past barriers that currently hold humanity.  Non-probable futures allow humanity to identify aspects worth striving
for. Even if a world building exercise is not probable for instantiation within the built environment, people can inhabit
these environments virtually. What future do you want? Maybe working with NST can help us to create it.

COMMUNITY-LED DESIGN IDEATION
WITH PROFESSOR STEENBLIK FOR ABC
STEWART MONTESSORI SCHOOL
2
Community-Led Design Ideation
2
When ABC Stewart approached R. Spencer Steenblik and the Indiana University J. Irwin Miller
Architecture program in the fall of 2021, regarding the potential renovation or construction of a
new facility, his students in the graduate program began their research. First and foremost, the
students addressed the programmatic needs of the school and discussed initial expectations
and goals. One of the main suggestions from the research was to utilize “design thinking” to
encourage stakeholder engagement in the design process.
Design Thinking is the practice of using
iterative processes to understand users,
define problems, prototype ideas, and
test potential solutions.

Design thinking aims to put the users experience and needs at the center of the process
before exploring its feasibility and viability. Over the years, design thinking has become an
industry standard in the innovation space, helping countless companies, communities, and
individuals understand the problems they are facing. This process was popularized by the
Stanford D School and well known design company IDEO. Both of these groups refined their
processes and definitions over time, creating a whole category of research that aims to en­
gage stakeholders in the act of design. Interestingly, Columbus, Indiana too has a rich history
of inviting the community to be part of the design and implementation process for its many
architecture projects.
TRADITIONAL DESIGN THINKING

One of the best known frameworks for design thinking comes from the Stanford D School.
Their strategy involves the steps in the graphic above. They place an emphasis on under­
standing the audience, honing in on key questions, brainstorming solutions, building rep­
resentations of ideas, then testing the ideas against user feedback. Through continuous
iteration throughout the process, the ideas and prototypes get refined and tested with the
end users of the solution, ensuring the products and services stay rooted in human needs.
The double diamond. A classic visualization of the iterative process by
Design Council. (designcouncil.org.uk)
Interaction Design Foundation (interaction-design.org).
Easy Problem Solving (easyproblemsolving.com).

THE COLUMBUS WAY
For over two hundred years Columbus, Indiana
has worked to create a community that addresses

the concerns of all its citizens. With the growth of
Cummins Engine Co. and the rise of J. Irwin Miller
as its CEO in the 1940s, Columbus began to focus
more on the importance of architecture to invigorate
the fabric of the city. Miller championed a strategy for
growth and development that engaged the commu­
nity throughout the process. This framework eventu­
ally became known as the Columbus Way.
“The Columbus Way is a mindset that means staying
ahead of problems, encouraging and supporting
enlightened leadership, building for the future, investing in high standards, invoking participation
by all elements of the community, expressing concern for those in need and maintaining good
schools and educational institutions” (Tucker 4).

In 1964, J. Irwin Miller gave an historic speech at the opening of the Otter Creek golf course
and clubhouse. It was the perfect encapsulation of Miller’s ideas of corporate responsibility and
the ideal characteristics that make Columbus a wonderful place in which to live. Its progressive
attitude toward community engagement made Columbus unique in the landscape of the United
States.
As Miller wrote, “...we would like to see this community come to be, not the cheapest, but the
very best community of its size in the country.”
“We would like to see [Columbus] become the city in which the smartest, ablest, and best
young families would like to live; a community open in every respect to persons of every race,

color, and opinion; one that makes them feel welcome and at home here; a community which
offers their children the best education; a community of outspoken churches, genuine cultural
interests, exciting opportunities for recreation, and a community whose citizens are themselves
well paid and who will not tolerate poverty for others.” (Miller, Dedication of Otter Creek Golf
Course).
IDEO: CO-DESIGNING SCHOOLS TOOLKIT
IDEO is a global design company that practices a concept
called human-centered design. They use design-thinking to
solve complex challenges and use a people-first approach to
design solutions.
In the fall of 2020, IDEO released the Co-Designing Schools
Toolkit - a collection of activities, research, and frameworks,
specifically designed to help local communities develop strat­

egies for empowering educators to improve their schools. This
toolkit guides learning in the research phase with the imple­
mentation of six steps.

THE STAKEHOLDER ENGAGEMENT PROCESS
The Community Education Coalition & CivicLab
Beginning its framework in 1997, the Community Education Coalition pulled together leaders
in education, business, and the community throughout Columbus Indiana and the surrounding
region. Their goal was simple, yet daunting; to align the local learning systems to the engine
of economic growth and to raise the quality of life for its residents. This passion for the civic
engagement process led to public-private partnerships which produced major buildings, national
recognition, and ongoing collaborations that encourage educational attainment for everyone.
This productive union of community stakeholders, business leaders, and educators soon  led to

new initiatives. In 2012, CiviLab was brought to life. Dedicated to advancing the practice of civic
collaboration, CivicLab builds on the long history of community engagement in Columbus. Thier
primary goal is to advance a relation-ship based, systems-building approach to solve complex
social problems. They workshop with communities around the country to redesign the way
stakeholders work together by presenting fundemental principles and frameworks in order to
bolster collaboration that improves the lives of its residents.

Community-Led Design Ideation
“The aim of this approach is to engage all stakeholders
throughout the entire design process, ensuring that the new
building and its programming serves the entire community
- including the students, parents, teachers and administra­
tors. By building empathy across all stakeholder groups,
and involving them throughout the entire process, not just in
the initial discovery and during the final prototype testing, we
position them as equal partners” (Lena Blackstock, Design
Research and Strategy).
“One of the challenges with the traditional design thinking
process when applied in large complex problem spaces, is
that empathy can become just a ‘step in the process’ and a
‘box to check’, whereas co-creation, participatory research,

and design approaches center the entire process around
the user’s lived experience and their needs. Co-creation
levels the playing field and creates space for all stakehold­
ers to impact design outcomes through participation. This
means we do research through design, not just research for
design” (Lena Blackstock, Design Research and Strategy).

AI Digital Future Expo: A Graduate Poster & Installation Session
The Arts and Humanities AI Digital Future Team and the College of Arts and Sciences are calling for
statements of interest to participate in a graduate poster/installation session. The selected applicants
are invited to host a booth at the Gayle Karch Cook Center for Public Arts and Humanities at IUB during a
half day interdisciplinary exchange on Saturday, March 2nd, 2024.
Concept sketch by Arthur Liou, AI Digital Future Expo, image generated in Midjourney
Topic:
We invite individuals and teams of graduate students in all disciplines at IUB and IUPUI to share their
research and creative activities on the social and cultural impact of technology such as artificial

intelligence, deep/machine learning, and large language models on our creative process, knowledge
generation/dissemination, tech-augmented expression, and new facets of human/machine
relationships.
Scope:
We welcome presentations at any stage of the research process ranging from formative inquiry and
works in progress, to late-stage research findings. We also invite any forms of theoretical articulations,
analytical observations, historical reflection, and/or creative interpretations of the topics.
Presentation Format:
Presentations may be made in the form of posters, art installations, screen-based content, performance,
or any combination of these. Presenters will be provided with a space and an optional 8-foot table.

Presenters are responsible for bringing their own equipment as needed. Power sources will be available
upon advanced request.
